Not necessarily...

MapSPAM uses quite a similar method to the one I outlined below. The
accuracy largely depends on the level of the inventory data (country
level being the least accurate, then state, then district etc.).

Perhaps a first step would be to investigate MapSPAM a bit further and
find out the level of inventory data they use for the countries we are
studying. In India, for example, the MapSPAM quantities match up quite
well at the district level, but I'm not sure about South America.

We could also downscale MapSPAM further using the ESA land cover map and
any other global remote sensing products which include irrigated
area.

Cheers,
Simon

